[2] Cholera - Iraq (multiple areas): WHO situation report
Date: Wed 19 Sep 2007
Source: UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA),
ReliefWeb, WHO report [edited]
<http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/RWB.NSF/db900SID/LSGZ-778GJS/$File/Full_Report.pdf>

New developments
----------------
- Baghdad: The 1st laboratory confirmed case of cholera of the Inaba
serotype, in Baghdad was reported on 19 Sep 2007 in a 25 year old female
who lives in Jisr Diala area/ Mada'en district of Baghdad Resafa. The case
is still [being treated in] Zaafraniyah hospital.
- Basra: (Modiana district) On 17 Sep 2007, a 7 month old breast and bottle
fed child, presented with fever and diarrhea for 6 days, and tested
positive for _Vibrio cholerae_ of the Inaba serotype. The isolate was sent
on 18 Sep 2007 to the CPHL [central public health laboratory] and confirmed
as _Vibrio cholerae_ of the Inaba serotype on the following day. 511 cases
of acute watery diarrhea were reported from Basra on 18 Sep 2007; out of
the 511 cases 17 were admitted to hospital. None of the 511 samples tested
was positive for _Vibrio cholerae_.
- Diala: the stool samples of 3 out of the 4 patients tested negative for
the cholera bacillus in Baquba General Hospital, however, all patients were
on antibiotics before collection of specimens. All are diagnosed by
treating doctors as cholera on clinical grounds. The 4th case is a 9 month
child admitted to Al-Batool pediatric hospital in Diala, stool specimen
results are not yet available.
- Tikrit: no secondary cases were reported following the case reported in
sitrep [situation report] 10.
- Mosul: despite high quality surveillance no additional suspect or
confirmed cases were reported from Mosul directorate of health following
cases reported in sitrep 10.
- Falluja: for the 1st time in 2 years, WHO was able to establish daily
reports with Falluja general hospital and Falluja district. Daily reports
shows that a diarrheal disease surveillance has been set up and stool
samples are collected from 15-19 per cent of admitted diarrhea cases. All
specimens collected since the beginning of the month [September 2007] have
been negative for the cholera bacillus.
--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Although this report comments on cases in Basra (Basra governate), Tikrit,
and Mosul (Ninawa governate) from a previous situation report, this has not
been reported here before and the list of cases in the full report found at
<http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/RWB.NSF/db900SID/LSGZ-778GJS/$File/Full_Report.pdf>
does not list a case in Tikrit:
